{"title_page": "Clara Stern (psychologist)", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Clara Stern\n| image              = \n| imagesize          = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Clara Joseephy\n| birth_date         = March 12, 1877\n| birth_place        = [[Berlin|Berlin, Germany]]\n| death_date         = 1945\n| burial_place       = \n| death_place        = \n| othername          = \n| occupation         = Psychologist\n| years_active       = \n| spouse             = [[William Stern (psychologist)|William Stern]] (1871\u20131938)\n| mother             = Friederike Benjamin\n| father             = Julius Joseephy\n| signature          = \n| children           = Hilde (1900\u20131962), \n[[G\u00fcnther Anders]] (1902\u20131992), \nEva (1904\u20131992)\n| nationality        = German-American\n}}\n'''Clara Stern''', (n\u00e9e '''Clara Joseephy''', (born March 12, 1877 in [[Berlin|Berlin, Germany]], died 1945) was an innovator in the field of [[developmental psychology]] with her husband, psychologist William Stern. \n\n== Biography ==\nClara was born into a wealthy Jewish family in [[Berlin|Berlin, Germany]]. Her father was the banker Julius Joseephy, her mother Friederike (n\u00e9e Benjamin) and she was born at the family's home.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deutsche-biographie.de/pnd117275387.html|title=Stern, Clara (verheiratete) - Deutsche Biographie|last=Biographie|first=Deutsche|website=www.deutsche-biographie.de|language=de|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.feministvoices.com/clara-stern/|title=Clara Stern - Psychology's Feminist Voices|last=James|first=Lamiell|date=2016|website=www.feministvoices.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nShe met [[William Stern (psychologist)|William Stern]] (1871 \u2013 1938) while on a bicycle ride through Berlin. Her parents were unhappy with the match (Stern had little money,), but Clara persisted despite her parents\u2019 disapproval and the two married early in 1899. William Stern became a professor of education at the [[University of Wroc\u0142aw|University of Breslau]] and the family prospered nearby.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://marcuse.faculty.history.ucsb.edu/projects/anders/andersbio.htm|title=G\u00fcnther Anders, 500 word biography|website=marcuse.faculty.history.ucsb.edu|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> (The city where they lived was then called [[Wroc\u0142aw|Breslau, Germany]], but it was renamed in 1945, after European borders were redrawn following [[World War II]], to [[Wroc\u0142aw|Wroc\u0142aw, Poland]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://forward.com/news/breaking-news/212310/poland-university-restores-262-phds-stripped-by-na/|title=Poland University Restores 262 PhD's Stripped by Nazis|last=JTAJanuary 8|last2=2015wikipedia|website=The Forward|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>)  \n\nTheir first daughter was Hilde (Marchwitza) (April 7, 1900\u20131962) who, in later years, became a resistance fighter against Nazi [[Nazism|National Socialism]] forces. Their son, a German essayist, technology critic and philosopher named G\u00fcnther (1902\u20131992) was followed by another daughter, Eva (1904\u20131992).<ref name=\":0\" /> (When he was a young journalist in Berlin, their son took the surname pseudonym [[G\u00fcnther Anders|Anders]], meaning \"other,\" to please his editor who \"had too many Sterns on his staff.\"<ref name=\":2\" />) \n\nThe Stern family moved from Breslau to [[Hamburg|Hamburg, Germany]] in 1916, where William was named a professor at the [[University of Hamburg]].<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\n=== Work in child development ===\nClara and William Stern greatly influenced the field of child development. Using their three children as subjects, they studied several aspects of each child's language development as well as other aspects they thought might be relevant. They started by keeping a detailed diary for each child, carefully noting the development of each individual from the day each was born up until they were 12, 10, and 7 years old, respectively. In almost 5,000 handwritten pages of notes,<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=Diehl|first=Manfred|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jDKcBQAAQBAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA4&dq=psychologist+Clara+Stern&hl=en|title=Handbook of Intraindividual Variability Across the Life Span|last2=Hooker|first2=Karen|last3=Sliwinski|first3=Martin J.|date=2014-12-08|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=978-1-136-28523-3|location=|pages=4|language=en}}</ref> the data that they recorded included reactions, babbling, the ability to recall events, lying and moral judgment.<ref name=\":4\" /> \n\nIn addition, by systematically recording one-to-one sessions with each child, one parent would begin storytelling and while the other parent, typically Clara, would take detailed notes. (The majority of the written entries were made by Clara Stern.<ref name=\":4\" />) By evaluating their cumulative observations of all three children, the Sterns founded the concept of \"game theory,\" which states that a child's personal development depends on the quality of the child's play.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|last=G\u00f6rlitz|first=Dietmar|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nqn-pw4dZaUC&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA339&dq=psychologist+Clara+Stern&hl=en|title=Children, Cities, and Psychological Theories: Developing Relationships|last2=Harloff|first2=Hans-Joachim|last3=Mey|first3=G\u00fcnter|last4=Valsiner|first4=Jaan|date=1998|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|year=|isbn=978-3-11-014603-5|location=|pages=339|language=en}}</ref>\n\nSome of their work was groundbreaking, according to G\u00f6rlitz.<ref name=\":4\" /><blockquote>\"During the second year of life, for example, almost all children begin to designate themselves or other people linguistically. Children growing up in a German-speaking environment differ in terms of whether their first self-designation consists of a name or a pronoun. Clara and William Stern discovered that their firstborn (a daughter) first designated herself with a name, whereas her two younger siblings started designating themselves with a pronoun. Ninety years later, this sibling effect, first discovered in case studies from just one family, has been replicated in large samples taken from different cultures and languages.\"<ref name=\":4\" /></blockquote>The children later reported that they hardly noticed any of these observations. <ref name=\":4\" /> \n\n=== Emigration ===\n[[File:G\u00fcnther Stern and Hannah Arendt.jpg|thumb|G\u00fcnther (Stern) Anders and his wife Hannah (c. 1929)]]\nWith the domination of governmental power in Germany by the [[Nazism|Nazis]] in 1933, Jewish scholars were systematically removed from their professional positions and William Stern was forced to give up management of his psychological institute and his functions on all committees at the [[University of Hamburg]]. Warned by their 31-year-old son G\u00fcnther that Hitler's ultimate aim was the extermination of the Jews, the Stern couple went into exile abroad, first to the [[Netherlands]] and then to the United States. [[Duke University]] in [[Durham, North Carolina]] offered William Stern a professorship in the Department of Psychology that ensured the couple's livelihood.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nWilliam Stern is widely remembered as the originator of the [[Intelligence quotient|Intelligence Quotient]] (I.Q.).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://library.duke.edu/rubenstein/findingaids/uastern/|title=Guide to the William Stern Papers, 1937-1938, undated|website=David M. Rubenstein Rare Book & Manuscript Library|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> He died 27 March 1938 in Durham.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nClara Stern died in 1945.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deutsche-biographie.de/sfz116015.html|title=Stern, Clara (verheiratete) - Deutsche Biographie|last=Biographie|first=Deutsche|website=www.deutsche-biographie.de|language=de|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://data.bibliotheken.nl/doc/thes/p069373124|title=Library of the Netherlands|last=Stern|first=Clara|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> \n\n== Writings ==\nThe results of the Stern's collaborative research were summarized in their three books, which listed Clara as first author.\n\n* Clara and William Stern: ''The Children's Language''. 1907, (Reprint Scientific Book Society Darmstadt,1987 )\n* Clara and William Stern: ''Memory, Statement and Lies in the First Childhood''. 1908\n* Clara and William Stern: ''Psychology of Early Childhood up to the Sixth Year''. 1914 (Clara Stern translated the third edition of this book into English and that text was published in 1924.)<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite book|last=STERN|first=William|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TGkjzAEACAAJ&newbks=0&hl=en|title=Psychology of Early Childhood Up to the Sixth Year of Age: Suppl. by Extracts from the Unpublished Diaries of Clara Stern|date=1924|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Honors ==\nAccording to James Lamiell'',''<ref name=\":1\" /> \"Bestowed posthumously on Clara Stern at the [[Max Planck Society|Max Planck Institute]] for [[Psycholinguistics]] in [[Nijmegen|Nijmegen, Holland]]... one can view the busts of nine individuals judged by a panel of distinguished scientists to have made extraordinary contributions to the discipline of psycholinguistics.\u00a0The eight busts alongside that of Clara Stern are those of (in alphabetical order) [[Paul Broca]], [[Karl B\u00fchler]], [[Franciscus Donders|F. C. Donders]], [[Roman Jakobson]], [[Edward Sapir]], [[William Stern (psychologist)|William Stern]], [[Carl Wernicke]], and [[Wilhelm Wundt]] \u2013 all widely known and highly respected historical luminaries, and all males.\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|3}}\n\n== External sources ==\n\n* Deutsch W. (2011) Clara Stern: Living for science as a woman and mother. In: Volkmann-Raue S., L\u00fcck H. (eds) Important psychologists of the 20th century. VS Publishing house for social sciences: https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-3-531-93064-0_8 (in German)\n* Werner Deutsch & Christliebe El Mogharbel (2011) Clara and William Stern's conception of a developmental science, European Journal of Developmental Psychology, 8:2, 135-156, DOI: 10.1080/17405629.2010.537548\n* Sibylle Volkmann-Raue (ed.): ''Important psychologists. Biographies and writings''. Beltz-Vlg, Weinheim 2002, ISBN 3-407-22136-3\n\n<br />\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stern, Clara}}\n\n[[Category:1877 births]]\n[[Category:1945 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Berlin]]\n[[Category:Scientists from Berlin]]\n[[Category:German Jews]]\n[[Category:Jewish German scientists]]\n[[Category:Jewish emigrants from Nazi Germany to the United States]]\n[[Category:Jewish women scientists]]\n[[Category:Women psychologists]]\n[[Category:Psychologists by century]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Clara Stern\n| image              = \n| imagesize          = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Clara Joseephy\n| birth_date         = March 12, 1877\n| birth_place        = [[Berlin|Berlin, Germany]]\n| death_date         = 1945\n| burial_place       = \n| death_place        = \n| othername          = \n| occupation         = Psychologist\n| years_active       = \n| spouse             = [[William Stern (psychologist)|William Stern]] (1871\u20131938)\n| mother             = Friederike Benjamin\n| father             = Julius Joseephy\n| signature          = \n| children           = Hilde (1900\u20131962), \n[[G\u00fcnther Anders]] (1902\u20131992), \nEva (1904\u20131992)\n| nationality        = German-American\n}}\n'''Clara Stern''', (n\u00e9e '''Clara Joseephy''', (born March 12, 1877 in [[Berlin|Berlin, Germany]], died 1945) was an innovator in the field of [[developmental psychology]] with her husband, psychologist William Stern. \n\n== Biography ==\nClara was born into a wealthy Jewish family in [[Berlin|Berlin, Germany]]. Her father was the banker Julius Joseephy, her mother Friederike (n\u00e9e Benjamin) and she was born at the family's home.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deutsche-biographie.de/pnd117275387.html|title=Stern, Clara (verheiratete) - Deutsche Biographie|last=Biographie|first=Deutsche|website=www.deutsche-biographie.de|language=de|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.feministvoices.com/clara-stern/|title=Clara Stern - Psychology's Feminist Voices|last=James|first=Lamiell|date=2016|website=www.feministvoices.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nShe met [[William Stern (psychologist)|William Stern]] (1871 \u2013 1938) while on a bicycle ride through Berlin. Her parents were unhappy with the match (Stern had little money,), but Clara persisted despite her parents\u2019 disapproval and the two married early in 1899. William Stern became a professor of education at the [[University of Wroc\u0142aw|University of Breslau]] and the family prospered nearby.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://marcuse.faculty.history.ucsb.edu/projects/anders/andersbio.htm|title=G\u00fcnther Anders, 500 word biography|website=marcuse.faculty.history.ucsb.edu|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> (The city where they lived was then called [[Wroc\u0142aw|Breslau, Germany]], but it was renamed in 1945, after European borders were redrawn following [[World War II]], to [[Wroc\u0142aw|Wroc\u0142aw, Poland]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://forward.com/news/breaking-news/212310/poland-university-restores-262-phds-stripped-by-na/|title=Poland University Restores 262 PhD's Stripped by Nazis|last=JTAJanuary 8|last2=2015wikipedia|website=The Forward|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>)  \n\nTheir first daughter was Hilde (Marchwitza) (April 7, 1900\u20131962) who, in later years, became a resistance fighter against Nazi [[Nazism|National Socialism]] forces. Their son, a German essayist, technology critic and philosopher named G\u00fcnther (1902\u20131992) was followed by another daughter, Eva (1904\u20131992).<ref name=\":0\" /> (When he was a young journalist in Berlin, their son took the surname pseudonym [[G\u00fcnther Anders|Anders]], meaning \"other,\" to please his editor who \"had too many Sterns on his staff.\"<ref name=\":2\" />) \n\nThe Stern family moved from Breslau to [[Hamburg|Hamburg, Germany]] in 1916, where William was named a professor at the [[University of Hamburg]].<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\n=== Work in child development ===\nClara and William Stern greatly influenced the field of child development. Using their three children as subjects, they studied the children's language development as well as other aspects of child development. They started by keeping a detailed diary for each child, carefully noting the development of each individual from the day each was born up until they were 12, 10, and 7 years old, respectively. In almost 5,000 handwritten pages of notes,<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=Diehl|first=Manfred|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jDKcBQAAQBAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA4&dq=psychologist+Clara+Stern&hl=en|title=Handbook of Intraindividual Variability Across the Life Span|last2=Hooker|first2=Karen|last3=Sliwinski|first3=Martin J.|date=2014-12-08|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=978-1-136-28523-3|location=|pages=4|language=en}}</ref> the data that they recorded included reactions, babbling, the ability to recall events, lying and moral judgment. The majority of the written entries were made by Clara Stern.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nThe couple even began systematically recording sessions where the child would elicit story narratives and descriptions with one parent while the other kept detailed notes. Through their observations, the Sterns found what they called \"game theory,\" which says that a child's play is necessary for personal development.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|last=G\u00f6rlitz|first=Dietmar|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nqn-pw4dZaUC&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA339&dq=psychologist+Clara+Stern&hl=en|title=Children, Cities, and Psychological Theories: Developing Relationships|last2=Harloff|first2=Hans-Joachim|last3=Mey|first3=G\u00fcnter|last4=Valsiner|first4=Jaan|date=1998|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|year=|isbn=978-3-11-014603-5|location=|pages=339|language=en}}</ref>\n\nSome of their work was groundbreaking, according to G\u00f6rlitz.<ref name=\":4\" /><blockquote>\"During the second year of life, for example, almost all children begin to designate themselves or other people linguistically. Children growing up in a German-speaking environment differ in terms of whether their first self-designation consists of a name or a pronoun. Clara and William Stern discovered that their firstborn (a daughter) first designated herself with a name, whereas her two younger siblings started designating themselves with a pronoun. Ninety years later, this sibling effect, first discovered in case studies from just one family, has been replicated in large samples taken from different cultures and languages.\"<ref name=\":4\" /></blockquote>The children later reported that they hardly noticed any of these observations. <ref name=\":4\" /> \n\n=== Emigration ===\n[[File:G\u00fcnther Stern and Hannah Arendt.jpg|thumb|G\u00fcnther (Stern) Anders and his wife Hannah (c. 1929)]]\nWith the domination of governmental power in Germany by the [[Nazism|Nazis]] in 1933, Jewish scholars were systematically removed from their professional positions and William Stern was forced to give up management of his psychological institute and his functions on all committees at the [[University of Hamburg]]. Warned by their 31-year-old son G\u00fcnther that Hitler's ultimate aim was the extermination of the Jews, the Stern couple went into exile abroad, first to the [[Netherlands]] and then to the United States. [[Duke University]] in [[Durham, North Carolina]] offered William Stern a professorship in the Department of Psychology that ensured the couple's livelihood.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nWilliam Stern is widely remembered as the originator of the [[Intelligence quotient|Intelligence Quotient]] (I.Q.).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://library.duke.edu/rubenstein/findingaids/uastern/|title=Guide to the William Stern Papers, 1937-1938, undated|website=David M. Rubenstein Rare Book & Manuscript Library|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> He died 27 March 1938 in Durham.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nClara Stern died in 1945.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deutsche-biographie.de/sfz116015.html|title=Stern, Clara (verheiratete) - Deutsche Biographie|last=Biographie|first=Deutsche|website=www.deutsche-biographie.de|language=de|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://data.bibliotheken.nl/doc/thes/p069373124|title=Library of the Netherlands|last=Stern|first=Clara|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> \n\n== Writings ==\nThe results of the Stern's collaborative research were summarized in their three books, which listed Clara as first author.\n\n* Clara and William Stern: ''The Children's Language''. 1907, (Reprint Scientific Book Society Darmstadt,1987 )\n* Clara and William Stern: ''Memory, Statement and Lies in the First Childhood''. 1908\n* Clara and William Stern: ''Psychology of Early Childhood up to the Sixth Year''. 1914 (Clara Stern translated the third edition of this book into English and that text was published in 1924.)<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite book|last=STERN|first=William|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TGkjzAEACAAJ&newbks=0&hl=en|title=Psychology of Early Childhood Up to the Sixth Year of Age: Suppl. by Extracts from the Unpublished Diaries of Clara Stern|date=1924|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Honors ==\nAccording to James Lamiell'',''<ref name=\":1\" /> \"Bestowed posthumously on Clara Stern at the [[Max Planck Society|Max Planck Institute]] for [[Psycholinguistics]] in [[Nijmegen|Nijmegen, Holland]]... one can view the busts of nine individuals judged by a panel of distinguished scientists to have made extraordinary contributions to the discipline of psycholinguistics.\u00a0The eight busts alongside that of Clara Stern are those of (in alphabetical order) [[Paul Broca]], [[Karl B\u00fchler]], [[Franciscus Donders|F. C. Donders]], [[Roman Jakobson]], [[Edward Sapir]], [[William Stern (psychologist)|William Stern]], [[Carl Wernicke]], and [[Wilhelm Wundt]] \u2013 all widely known and highly respected historical luminaries, and all males.\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|3}}\n\n== External sources ==\n\n* Deutsch W. (2011) Clara Stern: Living for science as a woman and mother. In: Volkmann-Raue S., L\u00fcck H. (eds) Important psychologists of the 20th century. VS Publishing house for social sciences: https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-3-531-93064-0_8 (in German)\n* Werner Deutsch & Christliebe El Mogharbel (2011) Clara and William Stern's conception of a developmental science, European Journal of Developmental Psychology, 8:2, 135-156, DOI: 10.1080/17405629.2010.537548\n* Sibylle Volkmann-Raue (ed.): ''Important psychologists. Biographies and writings''. Beltz-Vlg, Weinheim 2002, ISBN 3-407-22136-3\n\n<br />\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stern, Clara}}\n\n[[Category:1877 births]]\n[[Category:1945 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Berlin]]\n[[Category:Scientists from Berlin]]\n[[Category:German Jews]]\n[[Category:Jewish German scientists]]\n[[Category:Jewish emigrants from Nazi Germany to the United States]]\n[[Category:Jewish women scientists]]\n[[Category:Women psychologists]]\n[[Category:Psychologists by century]]\n", "name_user": "AMM Pittsburgh", "label": "safe", "comment": "copy editing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clara_Stern_(psychologist)