 and Zintan,[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/africaandindianocean/libya/8404944/Libya-Gaddafi-loyalists-in-Ajdabiya-seeking-to-surrender.html] of which 30 were killed in Misrata,[http://blogs.aljazeera.net/live/africa/libya-live-blog-march-24] 6 killed in Zintan (4 April),[http://blogs.aljazeera.net/live/africa/libya-live-blog-april-4] 15 killed in Wazzin (21 April),{{cite web |url=http://www.agi.it/english-version/world/elenco-notizie/201104211843-cro-ren1081-libyan_insurgents_gain_control_of_border_pass |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-04-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110424035236/http://www.agi.it/english-version/world/elenco-notizie/201104211843-cro-ren1081-libyan_insurgents_gain_control_of_border_pass |archivedate=24 April 2011 |df=dmy }} 45 killed near Nalut (25 April),[http://www.skynews.com.au/world/article.aspx?id=606123&vId=] 8 killed in Wazzin (28 April),[http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/afp_world/view/1125611/1/.html] 2 killed in Zintan (28 April),[https://web.archive.org/web/20120316101452/http://m.timesofindia.com/PDATOI/articleshow/8116794.cms] 3 killed in Wazzin (29 April),[http://blogs.aljazeera.net/live/africa/libya-live-blog-april-29] 21 killed in Nalut and Yafran (12\u201317 May),[http://www.libyanfsl.com/PDF/libyaHurra.PDF] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722154049/http://www.libyanfsl.com/PDF/libyaHurra.PDF |date=22 July 2011 }} 8 killed in al-Rayaniya (18 May),[http://www.wkbt.com/Global/story.asp?S=14671201]{{dead link|date=September 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}} 1 killed in Nalut (19 May),[http://www.miamiherald.com/2011/05/18/2223010/rebels-gadhafi-fighters-shell.html], 9 killed in Wazzin,[http://blogs.aljazeera.net/liveblog/libya-may-22-2011-2139] 8 killed in Yafran,[http://in.reuters.com/article/2011/06/01/libya-westernmountains-blockade-idINLDE75011E20110601] 100 killed in Al-Rayayna and Zawiet al-Baqool (12\u201313 June),[http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/06/13/libya.war/] 1 killed in Al-Rayayna (14 June),[https://ottawacitizen.com/news/Libyan+troops+shell+western+rebel+positions/4949468/story.html] 45 killed (17\u201318 June),[http://ca.reuters.com/article/topNews/idCATRE7270JP20110618] 5 killed (6 July),[https://www.nytimes.com/2011/07/13/world/africa/13libya.html?_r=1] 6 killed (6 August),[http://www.modernghana.com/columnnews/343960/1/libya-rebel-chief-urges-unity-as-nato-blasts-brega.html][http://hosted2.ap.org/COGRA/f29d8dad34bd498da777a4fb9802979d/Article_2011-08-06-ML-Libya/id-f51f31cc285b48508c7f64f223b9e664] total of 397 reported killed</ref><br>215<ref>52 in Nalut,[http://www.aljazeera.com/video/africa/2011/05/201152451012814342.html] 13 in Yafran,[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hVIZDIKxFSA] 50 in al-Galaa [https://ottawacitizen.com/story_print.html?id=4993607&sponsor=]{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} 147 captured in Zintan,[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/jul/14/libya-gaddafi-troops-demoralised-prisoners-of-war] total of 262 confirmed captured</ref> \u2013 295<ref>18 captured in Nalut (18 March),[https://af.reuters.com/article/tunisiaNews/idAFLDE72H11720110318] 3 captured in Yafran (15 April),[http://www.news24.com/Africa/News/Fighting-rages-in-Misrata-20110415] 14 captured in Wazin (21 April),[http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/04/21/libya.fighting/index.html?hpt=T1] 17 captured in Nalut (27 April),[http://www.skynews.com.au/world/article.aspx?id=606123&vId=] 32 captured in Kikla (28 May),[http://thestar.com.my/news/nastory.asp?file=/2011/5/28/worldupdates/2011-05-28T194201Z_01_NOOTR_RTRMDNC_0_-573443-4&sec=Worldupdates] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018111346/http://thestar.com.my/news/nastory.asp?file=%2F2011%2F5%2F28%2Fworldupdates%2F2011-05-28T194201Z_01_NOOTR_RTRMDNC_0_-573443-4&sec=Worldupdates |date=18 October 2012 }} 13 captured in Yafran (19 June),[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hVIZDIKxFSA] 50 captured in Al-Galaa (23 June),[https://ottawacitizen.com/story_print.html?id=4993607&sponsor=]{{dead link|date=September 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}} 1 captured (27 June),[http://english.aljazeera.net/video/africa/2011/06/201162723513413273.html] 147 captured in Zintan [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/jul/14/libya-gaddafi-troops-demoralised-prisoners-of-war] total of 295 reported captured</ref> captured**<br>several tanks destroyed**<br>10+ tanks or armoured vehicles captured<ref>{{cite web |author=Image Source: www.reuters.com |url=http://www.allvoices.com/contributed-news/9096747/image/79970002-a-rebel-fighter-checks-a-tank-captured-from-forces-loyal-to-libyan-leader-muammar-gaddafi |title=A rebel fighter checks a tank, captured from forces loyal to Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi in the rebel-held town of Zintan |publisher=Allvoices.com |accessdate=24 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121004182547/http://www.allvoices.com/contributed-news/9096747/image/79970002-a-rebel-fighter-checks-a-tank-captured-from-forces-loyal-to-libyan-leader-muammar-gaddafi |archive-date=4 October 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-13921665 |title=Libya: Fierce fighting south-west of Tripoli |publisher=BBC |date=27 June 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n|notes='''*'''The number of dead on the rebel side also includes civilians.<br>'''**'''Based largely on unconfirmed rebel claims\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Libyan civil war}}\n\nThe '''2011 Nafusa Mountains campaign''' was a series of battles in the [[2011 Libyan Civil War|Libyan Civil War]], fought between loyalist [[Libyan Armed Forces|pro-Gaddafi forces]] and rebel [[anti-Gaddafi forces]] in the [[Nafusa Mountains]] and, at a later period, in the surrounding plains of western Libya. The mountain range is of strategic importance due to its close proximity to the capital of [[Tripoli]]. Along with the city of [[Misrata]], the Nafusa Mountains region was one of the major rebel strongholds in [[Tripolitania]].\n\n== Background ==\nThe Nafusa mountains are heavily populated by ethnic [[Berbers]], a group which suffered intense persecution under Gaddafi's rule.<ref name=\"theglobeandmail.com\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/africa-mideast/small-rebel-victory-big-moment-for-persecuted-berber-tribes/article1995361/ |title=Small rebel victory big moment for persecuted Berber tribes |work=The Globe and Mail |location=Canada |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Gaddafi imposed bans on the teaching of the [[Berber language]] and on the use of traditional Berber names. In a 2008 diplomatic cable leaked by [[WikiLeaks]], Gaddafi warned Berber leaders \"You can call yourselves whatever you want inside your homes \u2013 Berbers, Children of Satan, whatever \u2013 but you are only Libyans when you leave your homes.\"<ref name=\"theglobeandmail.com\"/>\n\nOne of the first cities to stage protests against Gaddafi's rule in February 2011, was the town of [[Zintan]]. Zintan was home to several former Libyan military officers who participated in the failed [[1993 Libyan coup attempt]]; the city is thought to have high anti-Gaddafi sentiment.<ref name=\"3_News_203851\">{{cite web |url=http://www.3news.co.nz/Libya-Zintan-withdrawal-rare-success-for-rebels/tabid/417/articleID/203851/Default.aspx |title=Libya: Zintan withdrawal rare success for rebels |date=24 March 2011 |work=[[3 News]] |accessdate=15 September 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121001111621/http://www.3news.co.nz/Libya-Zintan-withdrawal-rare-success-for-rebels/tabid/417/articleID/203851/Default.aspx |archive-date=1 October 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nVery soon, the protests spread to the whole country and by the end of February most of the towns in the [[Nafusa Mountains]] were under opposition control.<ref name=\"v1d\">{{cite web|url=http://feb17.info/media/protests-continue-in-liberated-gharyan/ |title=Protests continue in Liberated Gharyan |date=26 February 2011 |publisher=Libyan Revolution Central |accessdate=25 March 2011 |location=Gharyan, Libya |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120312012800/http://feb17.info/media/protests-continue-in-liberated-gharyan/ |archivedate=12 March 2012 |df=dmy }}{{unreliable source?|date=August 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Campaign ==\n\n=== Loyalists retake Gharyan, rebels surrounded ===\n;1\u201320 March\nOn 1 March, loyalist forces started offensive operations south of Tripoli with the aim of retaking territory lost in previous days to the rebels. Their first target was the city of [[Gharyan]].\n\nGharyan was seen as a strategic town, because it was the largest in the Nafusa Mountains, a direct gateway to the [[Jabal al Gharbi District]] from Tripoli and was part of the defence ring loyalist forces were establishing around the capital.\n\nDuring the night between the 1 and 2 March, loyalist forces came into the town, under the cover of darkness. On the morning of 2 March, the rebels realised that the town was overrun by government troops. Soldiers had a list of opposition members and started to round up all of the rebels in Gharyan. Gharyan had been retaken by the government,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/article/304200|title=Pro and Anti-Gaddafi groups battle for strategic towns in Libya|last=Yuboco|first=Adeline|date=2 March 2011|work=Digital Journal|accessdate=25 March 2011|location=Libya}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.themarknews.com/news/?open=4256|title=Gadhafi Forces Strike at Rebel-Held Cities|date=2 March 2011|publisher=The Mark|accessdate=25 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110305073448/http://www.themarknews.com/news/?open=4256|archive-date=5 March 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.sina.com.hk/news/12/1/1/2031968/1.html|script-title=zh:\u53cd\u5c0d\u6d3e\u4fc3\u806f\u570b\u70b8\u5361\u624e\u83f2|last=\u83ef\u723e\u8857\u65e5\u5831|last2=\u8def\u900f\u793e|last3=\u885b\u5831|last4=\u6cd5\u65b0\u793e|date=3 March 2011|publisher=sina.com.hk|language=Chinese|accessdate=25 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110303235408/http://news.sina.com.hk/news/12/1/1/2031968/1.html|archive-date=3 March 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> on the same day as the nearby city of [[Sabratha]], located west of [[Tripoli]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/news/gaddafi-regime-said-to-be-in-control-of-three-towns-near-tripoli-news-international-ldcqkbffdde.html|title=Gaddafi regime said to be in control of three towns, near Tripoli|date=2 March 2011|publisher=sify news|accessdate=25 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nAs news of the retaking of Gharyan spread, the rebels found out that Gaddafi's forces were preparing an assault to retake Zintan, the first town in western Libya to throw off his rule. Around 40 trucks and armoured vehicles fitted with anti-aircraft guns were spotted 30&nbsp;kilometers away heading to the city.<ref name=\"english.aljazeera.net\">{{cite news|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/africa/2011/03/201132292210533490.html#|title=Misurata shelled as battle for Libya rages |accessdate=22 March 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110322142741/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/africa/2011/03/201132292210533490.html| archivedate= 22 March 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref> Young people in Zintan took the fight to pro-Gaddafi forces, launching a series of \"preventative attacks\" on army barracks, checkpoints and other installations to gather weapons and equipment. At sunset, the city had been attacked three times and all repelled.<ref>{{cite news|url=  http://blogs.aljazeera.net/live/africa/africa/2011/03/09/middle-east/2011/02/17/live-blog-libya?page=4|title=Live Blog \u2013 Libya March 2|publisher=Al Jazeera|date=2 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 March, loyalist forces attempted another attack on Zintan which resulted in the deaths of 5\u20136 rebels and later rebels claimed that some 20 loyalist soldiers were killed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/feb17voices/status/44833237427699731|title=Revolutionaries captured soldiers from battalion. 20 soldiers from battalion killed, 1 revolutionary killed.|date= 7 March 2011 }}</ref> Government troops did not manage to enter the town. However, they had surrounded it and positioned mobile Grad rocket-launchers on the outskirts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.france24.com/en/20110308-libyan-rebels-hold-southern-town-zintan-witness?quicktabs_1=1|title=Libyan rebels hold southern town Zintan: witness|date=8 March 2011}}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> By this point, government forces had also surrounded the towns of [[Yafran]] and [[Nalut]].\n\nOn 18 March, rebel forces from Nalut attacked a government checkpoint on the outskirts of the town. Four government soldiers and one rebel were killed in the fighting and 18 loyalist soldiers were captured.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/03/18/libya-misrata-bombard-idUSLDE72H0MV20110318?pageNumber=2|title=Gaddafi forces shell west Libya's Misrata, 25 dead|date= 18 March 2011 | agency=Reuters}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/tunisiaNews/idAFLDE72H11720110318|title=Libya rebels attack govt forces near Tunisia border|date= 18 March 2011 | agency=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n=== Zintan offensive stopped ===\n;21\u201331 March\n[[File:Tripolitanian Front-final.svg|thumb|right|300px|alt=|{{legend|#ff6f0f|Held by anti-Gaddafi protesters by 1 March (Checkered: Maximum Loyalists gains, April\u2013May)}}\n{{legend|#ff944b|Rebel advances by 1 August}}\n{{legend|#ffbd91|Rebel gains after the western coastal offensive in August}}\n{{legend|#aade87|Last loyalist pockets}}]]\nOn 21 March, the pro-Gaddafi forces launched an offensive against the city. By 22 March, loyalist troops were pushed back from the eastern outskirts of the town, but were still holding a foothold in the northern outskirts.<ref name=\"english.aljazeera.net\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.aljazeera.net/live/africa/africa/2011/03/09/africa/2011/02/24/live-blog-libya-feb-25|title=Libya Live Blog \u2013 23 March 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://in.reuters.com/article/2011/03/22/libya-zintan-bombardment-idINLDE72L1ZM20110322|title=Attack on Libya's Zintan kills at least 10-resident|accessdate=22 March 2011 | agency=Reuters|date=22 March 2011}}</ref> As of 24 March, heavy shelling of Zintan by artillery and tank fire was ongoing. The rebels claimed they captured or destroyed several tanks, seized trucks loaded with 1,200 Grad missiles and fuel tanks, and captured five Gaddafi troops.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.3news.co.nz/Libya-Zintan-withdrawal-rare-success-for-rebels/tabid/417/articleID/203851/Default.aspx|title=Libya: Zintan withdrawal rare success for rebels|accessdate=24 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121001111621/http://www.3news.co.nz/Libya-Zintan-withdrawal-rare-success-for-rebels/tabid/417/articleID/203851/Default.aspx|archive-date=1 October 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> During the offensive against Zintan, 16\u201321 people were killed in the town,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/africa/2011/03/201132292210533490.html|title=Misurata shelled as battle for Libya rages|accessdate=22 March 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110322142741/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/africa/2011/03/201132292210533490.html| archivedate= 22 March 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.businessspectator.com.au/bs.nsf/Article/WRAPUP-14-Gaddafi-tanks-move-in-again-on-besieged--F8UHL?opendocument&src=rss|title=Gaddafi resumes Misrata attacks|accessdate=24 March 2011}}</ref> eight of them rebels.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.news24.com/Africa/News/8-rebels-killed-in-Libyas-Zintan-20110324|title=8 rebels killed in Libya's Zintan|accessdate=24 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nAt the same time as the attack on Zintan started, there was fighting at Yafran in which nine people were killed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allvoices.com/contributed-news/8552573-libya-paris-insists-on-keeping-nato-a-distance/content/75656935-the-french-aircraft-carrier-charles-de-gaulle-sets-off-for-libya|title=Of 'violent confrontations' were held Monday and Tuesday in the region Yafran, south-west of Tripoli, between the rebels who control the region and the Libyan regime's forces, killing at least 9 dead, told AFP the inhabitants of this region.|date=23 March 2011|access-date=7 April 2011|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120718083616/http://www.allvoices.com/contributed-news/8552573-libya-paris-insists-on-keeping-nato-a-distance/content/75656935-the-french-aircraft-carrier-charles-de-gaulle-sets-off-for-libya|archive-date=18 July 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Shelling of towns, intermittent skirmishes ===\n;1\u201316 April\nOn 1 April, after a week of a lull in fighting, loyalist troops were on the move again. Government firing of Grad rockets was hitting the western side of Zintan. Government troops had surrounded the town of Kikla, 60 kilometers east of Zintan, and were attacking another nearby town of Aquilla<!-- is this another name for al-Galaa? -->.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.aljazeera.net/live/africa/libya-live-blog-april-1|title=Libya Live Blog \u2013 April 1|accessdate=1 April 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110401101336/http://blogs.aljazeera.net/live/africa/libya-live-blog-april-1| archivedate= 1 April 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 April, Yafran was shelled by loyalist artillery killing two people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/international/witness-gadhafi-forces-kill-two-in-libya-town-of-yafran-1.353797|title=Witness: Gadhafi forces kill two in Libya town of Yafran|date=3 April 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOn 4 April, government troops captured the town of Kikla and started a rocket bombardment of Nalut.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.aljazeera.net/live/africa/libya-live-blog-april-4|title=Libya Live Blog \u2013 April 4|date=4 April 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOn 5 April, Al Jazeera English reported that the rebels in Nalut and Zintan infiltrated Yafran and helped their allies there to fight against government forces. They were able to push back Gaddafi's forces from Yafran.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.aljazeera.net/live/africa/libya-live-blog-april-5 |title=Al Jazeera Live Blog 5th April |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=4 April 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 April, Al Jazeera English reported that NATO airstrikes struck weapons depots belonging to pro-Gaddafi forces located 15&nbsp;kilometers southeast of Zintan. Residents heard 14 explosions and saw some of the buildings burning.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.aljazeera.net/live/africa/libya-live-blog-april-8 |title=Al Jazeera English Live Blog \u2013 April 8, 10:40&nbsp;pm |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=7 April 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 April, refugees from al-Galaa told Reuters that Gaddafi's forces have been burning water wells with petroleum and killing sheep, and promised to \"rape all girls\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/libyaNews/idAFLDE73908B20110410?pageNumber=1&virtualBrandChannel=0 |title=Libyan refugees tell of region suffering in silence |agency=Reuters |date=10 April 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 April, Al Jazeera reported that [[anti-Gaddafi forces]] were able to take Zintan's western gate. Alongside this they were also able to stop loyalist forces from taking the road leading from Nalut to Tunis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.aljazeera.net/live/africa/libya-live-blog-april-12-0 |title=Libya Live Blog \u2013 April 12 &#124; Al Jazeera Blogs |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=12 April 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 April, Al Jazeera English reported that rebels had repelled loyalist forces in the al-Haraba district, west of Rihaibat, after some minor clashes. However, the towns in the area remained under siege.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.aljazeera.net/live/africa/libya-live-blog-april-14 |title=AJE Libya Live Blog \u2013 April 14, 5:35&nbsp;am |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=13 April 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 April, eight rebels were killed and 11 wounded in heavy fighting near Yafran in which they also captured several loyalist soldiers. The rebels also claimed that NATO air-strikes had hit loyalist armored units in the vicinity of both Yafran and Zintan.<ref>{{cite web|author=Location Settings |url=http://www.news24.com/Africa/News/Fighting-rages-in-Misrata-20110415 |title=Fighting rages in Misrata |publisher=News24.com |date=15 April 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== New loyalist offensive, rebel fight for supply line ===\n;17 April \u2013 1 May\nOn 17 April, a heavy artillery bombardment of all rebel-held areas in the [[Jabal al Gharbi District]] started and continued into the next day. The loyalist attack left 110 people dead, including both civilians and rebels, according to residents.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nypost.com/p/news/international/boat_with_libya_officers_reaches_VHuQvzgUT9630fMSUSRnhI?CMP=OTC-rss&FEEDNAME= |title=More than 100 reported dead in western Libyan district as 1,000 flee Misrata by sea |work=New York Post |date=18 April 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Loyalist forces were reported by the rebels to be \"within striking distance\" of [[Jadu, Libya|Jadu]] and [[Ar Rajban]], but had been once again repelled from Zintan and Nalut.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2011/apr/17/gadhafi-lays-siege-libyan-mountain-towns/?page=1 |title=Gadhafi lays siege to west mountain towns |work=The Washington Times |date=17 April 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe shelling continued on 19 April, with four more people killed in Nalut.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/04/19/us-libya-tunisia-mortars-idUSTRE73I6UZ20110419 |title=Libyan mortar shells hit Tunisia, follow refugees |agency=Reuters |accessdate=24 January 2012 |date=19 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 April, Al Jazeera reported that the opposition forces had seized the border crossing with Tunisia, [[Wazzin]], forcing one hundred Gaddafi soldiers to retreat into Tunisia where they handed themselves in to Tunisian authorities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.aljazeera.net/live/africa/libya-live-blog-april-21-0 |title=Libya Live Blog \u2013 April 21 &#124; Al Jazeera Blogs |publisher=Al Jazeera |accessdate=24 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110421105452/http://blogs.aljazeera.net/live/africa/libya-live-blog-april-21-0 |archivedate=21 April 2011 }}</ref> The rebels also claimed to have killed 15 soldiers<ref>[http://www.agi.it/english-version/world/elenco-notizie/201104211843-cro-ren1081-libyan_insurgents_gain_control_of_border_pass Libyan Insurgents Gain Control of Border Pass] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110424035236/http://www.agi.it/english-version/world/elenco-notizie/201104211843-cro-ren1081-libyan_insurgents_gain_control_of_border_pass |date=24 April 2011 }}</ref> and captured another 14 on the Libyan side of the border.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/04/21/libya.fighting/index.html?hpt=T1 |title=Libyan rebels wrest control of Tunisian border crossing |publisher=CNN |date=21 April 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> However, all of the 100 soldiers returned from Tunisia into Libya the next day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.aljazeera.net/live/africa/libya-live-blog-april-22 |title=Libya Live Blog \u2013 April 22 |publisher=Al Jazeera |accessdate=24 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110422104040/http://blogs.aljazeera.net/live/africa/libya-live-blog-april-22 |archivedate=22 April 2011 }}</ref>\n\nNATO reported that it conducted strikes against loyalist targets in the vicinity of Zintan on 22 April. Two tanks, two bunkers, and some buildings were claimed to had been hit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.aljazeera.net/live/africa/libya-live-blog-april-23 |title=AJE Libya Live Blog \u2013 April 23, 5:05&nbsp;pm |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=22 April 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 April, rebels started to bring in supplies, through the border crossing at Wazzin, to the towns under siege. However, the same day it was reported that Yafran had been taken by loyalist forces.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/04/23/libya-idUSLDE73L0NL20110423 Libya troops retreat in Misrata, rebels claim victory]</ref>\n\nOn 24 April, a loyalist artillery barrage hit the border crossing at Wazzin in an attempt to recapture the town.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thejakartaglobe.com/afp/misrata-fighting-rages-on-despite-tripoli-vow/437209 |title=Misrata fighting rages on despite Tripoli vow |accessdate=24 April 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120923201001/http://www.thejakartaglobe.com/afp/misrata-fighting-rages-on-despite-tripoli-vow/437209 |archivedate=23 September 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> Also, four people were killed and nine wounded when Grad rockets hit Zintan.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.aljazeera.net/live/africa/libya-live-blog-april-25|title=Libya Live Blog \u2013 April 25|accessdate=25 April 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110425103749/http://blogs.aljazeera.net/live/africa/libya-live-blog-april-25| archivedate= 25 April 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref> The next day, two rebels were killed and three wounded in further fighting near Nalut in which the rebels claimed to had killed 45 loyalist soldiers and captured 17, although no independent sources could confirm the opposition's claims.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.skynews.com.au/world/article.aspx?id=606123&vId=|title=Rebels gain ground on Gaddafi|accessdate=27 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 April, [[Voice of Russia]] reported that rebels were still resisting in [[Yafran]] in spite of the pro-Gaddafi forces advance into the town two days previously.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://english.ruvr.ru/2011/04/25/49411782.html |title=Gaddafi troops encircle towns in west of Libya |publisher=English.ruvr.ru |date=25 April 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110429165909/http://english.ruvr.ru/2011/04/25/49411782.html |archive-date=29 April 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn 27 April, rebels claimed that loyalists fired at least 20 Grad rockets into the city centre of Zintan. Five houses were destroyed in the bombardment, which also damaged a local hospital and left three people injured.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.aljazeera.net/live/africa/libya-live-blog-april-27 |title=AJE Libya Live Blog \u2013 April 27, 3:45&nbsp;pm |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=26 April 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.aljazeera.net/live/africa/libya-live-blog-april-28 |title=AJE Libya Live Blog \u2013 April 28, 3:24&nbsp;am |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=27 April 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[The Daily Telegraph]] reported that RAF warplanes under NATO command attacked loyalist vehicles in the region, striking a tank near [[Mizda]] and destroying a self-propelled gun near Yafran.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/africaandindianocean/libya/libya-video/8475933/Coalition-increases-air-strikes-on-Libya.html |title=Coalition increases air strikes on Libya |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK |date=27 April 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 April, loyalist forces re-captured the Wazzin border crossing with Tunisia after a swift advance in which they pushed the rebels back over the border into Tunisia where the fighting continued on the edge of the Tunisian border town of Dehiba.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.aljazeera.net/live/africa/libya-live-blog-april-28 |title=Libya Live Blog \u2013 April 28 |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=27 April 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> State TV stated that several rebels were killed and others captured in the attack on the border post.<ref>{{cite news|last=Noueihed |first=Lin |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/04/28/us-libya-idUSTRE7270JP20110428 |title=Libyan forces overrun rebels on Tunisian border |agency=Reuters |accessdate=24 January 2012 |url-status=dead |date=28 April 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111227104712/https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/04/28/us-libya-idUSTRE7270JP20110428 |archivedate=27 December 2011 }}</ref> Later during the day, the rebels attempted a counter-attack.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/libyaNews/idAFLDE73R2BI20110428 |title=New clashes between Libyans at Tunisia border post |agency=Reuters |date=28 April 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Initially, they claimed to had re-taken the post. However, Reuters denied it later by confirming that the loyalists were still in full control.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/libyaNews/idAFLDE73R2C820110428 |title=Gaddafi forces still at Tunisia border -witness |agency=Reuters |date=28 April 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> During the confusion when it was thought that the rebels had won scores of civilian vehicles attempted to re-enter Libya from Tunisia. But, they quickly turned back when they found Gaddafi's forces were still at the border crossing.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/04/28/libya-idUSLDE73R2EO20110428 |title=WRAPUP 1-Libya angers Tunisia as war briefly crosses border |agency=Reuters |accessdate=24 January 2012 |date=28 April 2011}}</ref> Heavy fighting continued into the night, with rebels apparently massing for a renewed attack against the better-armed loyalists<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.aljazeera.net/live/africa/libya-live-blog-april-28 |title=AJE Libya Live Blog \u2013April 28, 11:14&nbsp;pm |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=27 April 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> and during the evening the rebels once again claimed to had re-taken the crossing after they received reinforcements from Zintan. Still, this claim was also later found to be untrue.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/29/world/africa/29libya.html?partner=rss&emc=rss Rebels Register Small Gains in Western Libya]</ref>\n\nThe next morning, loyalist troops advanced from the crossing post of Wazzin in pursuit of the rebels, who had retreated onto Tunisian soil after a night of fighting, over the border and engaged them in the center of the town of Dehiba. Soon after that clashes between Gaddafi and Tunisian troops were reported, but the Tunisian news agency TAP said Tunisian forces only fired in the air and did not clash directly with the Libyans.<ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/news/world/2011-04-29-libya_n.htm Libyan forces breach border with Tunisia]</ref> The Tunisian military soon seized loyalist troops and led them back over the border. At the same time, the rebels claimed for a third time to had re-taken the border post which was apparently confirmed by an AFP news crew.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/topNews/idAFJOE73S00320110429?pageNumber=1&virtualBrandChannel=0 |title=Pro-Gaddafi forces clash with Tunisian military |agency=Reuters |date=29 April 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> However, after nightfall, Gaddafi's forces resumed their bombardment of the crossing in an apparent attempt to return and the government said it had regained control over the Libyan side of the border.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2011/04/30/libya-idUKLDE73S1U620110430 |title=Libya's Gaddafi offers ceasefire, but will not leave |agency=Reuters |accessdate=24 January 2012 |date=30 April 2011}}</ref> Meanwhile, air strikes hit Gaddafi forces surrounding the town of Zintan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nato.int/nato_static/assets/pdf/pdf_2011_04/20110429_110429-oup-update.pdf |title=NATO operational update, Operation Unified Protector, 28th April |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 May, a caller on Al Jazeera said that the city of Zintan came under attack from Grad missiles the previous day, and pro-Gaddafi forces attempted to enter the town. During the bombardment, NATO planes could be heard overhead.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.aljazeera.net/live/africa/libya-live-blog-may-1 |title=Al Jazeera Live Blog, 1st May |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=30 April 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The next day, it was reported that rebels in the town of Yafran were under heavy siege and running out of vital supplies,<ref name=\"reuters1\">{{cite news|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/libyaNews/idAFLDE7411M020110502?sp=true |title=Libyan mountain town facing starvation: residents |agency=Reuters |date=2 May 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> contradicting earlier reports by the rebels that the town was captured by loyalist forces. In addition, rebels had apparently retaken the border crossing at Wazzin, while they claimed that NATO air-strikes destroyed 10\u201312 loyalist vehicles east of Zintan.<ref name=\"reuters1\"/>\n\n=== War of attrition, new loyalist advances ===\n;1 \u2013 30 May\nOn 3 May, forces loyal to Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi bombarded the rebel-held town of Zintan in the Western Mountains with over 40 Grad rockets late on Tuesday, a rebel spokesman said. \"They were fired in two salvoes,\" the spokesman, named Abdulrahman, said by telephone. \"The last salvo landed moments ago. We can hear NATO aircraft overhead now.\" A Libyan ambulance driver from Zintan who crossed into Tunisia on Tuesday told Reuters the town had come under intense shelling by pro-Gaddafi forces.<ref>{{cite web |author=Source: reuters // Reuters |url=http://www.trust.org/alertnet/news/gaddafi-forces-bombard-rebel-held-zintan-rebels |title=Gaddafi forces bombard rebel-held Zintan \u2013 rebels \u2013 AlertNet |publisher=Trust.org |date=3 May 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120406115944/http://www.trust.org/alertnet/news/gaddafi-forces-bombard-rebel-held-zintan-rebels |archive-date=6 April 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It was reported that 55 civilians were killed or wounded in the shelling.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.aljazeera.net/live/africa/libya-live-blog-may-3 |title=Libya Live Blog \u2013 May 3 |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=3 May 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 May, 11 rebels were killed and 50 wounded, some critically, during another advance by loyalist troops towards Zintan's eastern edge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wires.univision.com/english/article/2011-05-07/kadhafi-steps-up-assault-on |title=Kadhafi steps up assault on rebels across Libya |publisher=Wires.univision.com |date=7 May 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 May, it was reported that two rebels were killed and 15 wounded after coming under sniper fire in the village of Rya Ina, 9 miles east of Zintan. Loyalist snipers also fired on an ambulance transporting a wounded person, but no casualties were reported.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gilligan |first=Andrew |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/africaandindianocean/libya/8508488/Libya-rebels-celebrate-seizing-Misurata-airport.html |title=Libya: rebels celebrate seizing Misurata airport |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK |accessdate=24 January 2012 |date=11 May 2011}}</ref> Six rebels were also killed in an attempt to block a road used by loyalists, which resulted in an exchange of fire with pro-Gaddafi villagers.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://af.reuters.com/article/libyaNews/idAFLDE74B0RG20110512?pageNumber=2&virtualBrandChannel=0 | agency=Reuters | title=Geography thwarts Gaddafi on Libya's western front | date=12 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 May, rebels in the Nafusa Mountains issued a call for help to the National Transitional Council in the hopes of alleviating the constant loyalist siege on their towns.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/05/17/libya.war/ | publisher=CNN | title=Rebel forces in Libya's western mountains issue call for help | date=18 May 2011}}</ref> The same day, Al Jazeera English, citing rebel fighters from in and near Yafran, reported that the town had been cut off from food and medical supplies as a result of loyalist attacks with rockets and Grad missiles. Pro-Gaddafi forces were intensifying their shelling of towns in the upper part of the mountain range in an attempt to dislodge rebels from the high ground.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.aljazeera.net/liveblog/libya-may-18-2011-1325 |title=Libya \u2013 May 18, 2011 \u2013 13:25 |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=18 May 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nAt dawn on 19 May, Gaddafi forces have unleashed their biggest attack yet against Zintan. The attack started when about 150 loyalist infantry troops began firing on three fronts near the town. They were supported by about 40 vehicles, including long-range \"Grad\" rocket launchers and 14.5&nbsp;mm heavy machine guns with a range of 6 kilometers. The offensive continued well into the next day during which one rebel was killed and several wounded.<ref name=\"cnn.com\"/> On 21 May, the rebel commander in Zintan, Haji Usama, stated that he believed the intense loyalist attack was launched in order to capture the nearby town of Rayayan, the eastern half of which declared its support for the rebels a month previously. Although, the western half of Rayayan was reported to had stayed loyalist, partially due to the fact that former Gaddafi intelligence head [[Nasar al-Mabout]] lives there.<ref>{{cite news|author=From Nic Robertson, CNN |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/05/21/libya.zintan/ |title=Rebels battle Gadhafi forces in Libyan mountains |publisher=CNN |accessdate=24 January 2012 |date=24 August 2011}}</ref> Later, it was confirmed that, during the two days of heavy fighting, loyalist forces had managed to advance through the village of Al Rayayan and break through two rebel defence lines outside Zintan, despite NATO bombing runs on government troops and ammunition depots in the area.<ref>{{cite news|last=Robinson |first=Matt |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2011/05/25/uk-libya-westernmountains-idUKTRE74O2W520110525 |title=NATO war-lite means Libyan rebels must improvise |agency=Reuters |accessdate=24 January 2012 |date=25 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nBy 22 May, the town of al-Galaa, with a population of 16,000 people, was reported to be on the verge of being overrun by loyalist forces. Also, government troops had managed to captured the western part of Yafran, which includes the hospital, while rebels were still holding on to the eastern section of the city. Some 1,000 people were still in Yafran, half of them rebels.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/05/21/libya.small.towns/index.html?section=cnn_latest |title=Libyan begs NATO to save his small town |publisher=CNN |date=21 May 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Loyalists once again attempted to capture the Wazzin border crossing, according to rebels. One rebel and nine loyalists were killed before the pro-Gaddafi forces retreated back to positions in the vicinity of Rayayan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.aljazeera.net/liveblog/libya-may-22-2011-2139 |title=Libya \u2013 May 22, 2011 \u2013 21:39 |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=22 May 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, allegiances amongst part of the Nafusa mountain population remained unclear, as the towns (generally held by forces loyal to Gaddafi) on the plains north of the mountain provide a lot of the food resources in this arid region. Military campaigning from the rebel forces on 22 and 23 May, to take definite control on the mountain towns of Tamzin and Ar-Rayyan (Al Rayayna) met with mixed success. Reportedly, many villagers and townspeople were hesitant to take sides in the conflict, in part due to fear of reprisals from Gaddafi forces.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/05/23/us-libya-westernmountains-loyalty-idUSTRE74M1W020110523 War tests loyalties in Libya's rebel west (Reuters, 23 May)]</ref>\n\nOn 24 May, rebel commanders in Zintan stated that villages in Zintan's surroundings were in danger of falling very soon. By this point, loyalist forces were only 10 kilometers from Zintan.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/video/#/video/world/2011/05/24/robertson.zintan.fighting.cnn |title=Zintan, Libya, under fire |publisher=CNN |date=16 July 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 May, overnight the town of Zintan came under heavy rocket attack from Gaddafi forces, a foreign doctor told Reuters. \"There must have been about a hundred (strikes). I wasn't counting, but there were four or five rockets every half an hour or 15 minutes,\" Anja Wolz of Doctors Without Borders said by telephone. He stated that no one was seriously hurt, but the next day the doctors evacuated from the city due to the shelling.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/libyaNews/idAFLDE74Q0M820110527 |title=Libya's Zintan under heavy rocket attack \u2013 doctor |agency=Reuters |date=27 May 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 May, the rebels stated that five civilians died in Yafran and al-Galaa due to the fighting and of heart attacks. They also claimed to have attacked loyalist forces at Kikla and captured 32 government soldiers in fighting that also killed three rebels.<ref name=\"thestar.com.my\">{{cite web |url=http://thestar.com.my/news/nastory.asp?file=/2011/5/28/worldupdates/2011-05-28T194201Z_01_NOOTR_RTRMDNC_0_-573443-4&sec=Worldupdates |title=NATO says destroyed Gaddafi compound guard towers |work=The Star |location=Malaysia |date=23 November 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018111346/http://thestar.com.my/news/nastory.asp?file=%2F2011%2F5%2F28%2Fworldupdates%2F2011-05-28T194201Z_01_NOOTR_RTRMDNC_0_-573443-4&sec=Worldupdates |archive-date=18 October 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Also, a rebel spokesman confirmed that Yafran had fallen under loyalist control.<ref name=\"thestar.com.my\"/> Al-Galaa and a few small towns to the east of Yafran remained under tenuous rebel control.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.aljazeera.net/liveblog/libya-jun-2-2011-0939 |title=Thursday, June 2, 2011 \u2013 08:39 \u2013 Libya |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=2 June 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Rebel counterattack ===\n;1 June \u2013 6 July\nOn 1 June, rebels captured the towns of [[Shakshuk]] and [[Gasr Al-Hajj]], located in the plains north of the mountains. Shakshuk is home to a critical power station that supplies electricity to many towns in the mountains, and rebels hoped to use it to bring electricity back to the mountains.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.realclearworld.com/news/reuters/international/2011/Jun/01/libya_oil_chief_defects__nato_extends_campaign.html |title=Libya oil chief defects, NATO extends campaign |publisher=Realclearworld.com |date=1 June 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120311045227/http://www.realclearworld.com/news/reuters/international/2011/Jun/01/libya_oil_chief_defects__nato_extends_campaign.html |archive-date=11 March 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.aljazeera.net/liveblog/libya-jun-2-2011-0741 |title=Al Jazeera Live Blog |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=2 June 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> On 2 June, rebels reported that they had recaptured Yafran from loyalist forces as part of the same offensive supported by NATO airstrikes on loyalist positions near the town.<ref>{{cite web|author=DIAA HADID and RYAN LUCAS Associated Press |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Business/wireStory?id=13751953 |title=Rebels in Western Libya Seize Mountain Towns |publisher=ABC News |date=3 June 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Rebel fighters in Zintan reported that they had recaptured the town of Kikla and were surrounding al-Rayayna and Bir Ayyad which lies between Zintan and the besieged towns of Yefran and Al Galaa.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/06/03/libya.war/ |title=NATO airstrikes hit Yefren, Libya, where rebels claim liberation |publisher=CNN |accessdate=24 January 2012 |date=24 August 2011}}</ref><ref>[http://english.aljazeera.net/news/africa/2011/06/201163182012680622.html Rebel fighters make gains in western Libya ]</ref>\n\nOn 4 June, rebels captured the crossroads town of Bir Ayyad, which opened the road to the besieged cities of Yafran and Al Galaa.<ref>{{cite news|last=Graff |first=Peter |url=http://in.reuters.com/article/2011/06/04/idINIndia-57476220110604 |title=China meets Libya rebels in latest blow to Gaddafi |agency=Reuters |accessdate=24 January 2012 |date=4 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 June, Reuters journalists entered Yafran with rebel fighters, confirming earlier rebel reports that they had completely retaken the city.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/commoditiesNews/idAFLDE75510120110606 |title=Libyan rebels enter Gaddafi-held town of Yafran |agency=Reuters |date=6 June 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 June 10 rebels were killed<ref>{{cite news|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2011/06/13/libya-idUKLDE75C1JB20110613 |title=Libyan rebels edge westwards out of Misrata |agency=Reuters |accessdate=24 January 2012 |date=13 June 2011}}</ref> and 49 wounded<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.canada.com/news/story.html?id=4934305 |title=Battles rage in western Libya flashpoints: rebels |publisher=Canada.com |accessdate=24 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121110120814/http://www2.canada.com/news/story.html?id=4934305 |archive-date=10 November 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> in artillery attacks on Zintan.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/libyaNews/idAFLDE75C12S20110613 |title=Rebels say 9 killed in attack on Libya's Zintan |agency=Reuters |date=13 June 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> At the same time, rebels started their offensive on the village of Rayayna where they took control of half of the village.{{citation needed|date=November 2011}}\n\nOn 13 June, rebels captured the whole village of Al-Rayayna, where rebels claimed that 20 civilians had been killed. Rebels also attacked loyalist positions in nearby Zawiet al-Baqool, but the government troops still held firm. Talha Al-Jiwali, a rebel fighter, claimed that 100 loyalist soldiers died in both battles, while nine rebels were killed and 35 wounded at Al-Rayayna.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/06/13/libya.war/ |title=Rebels report advances in Libya's western mountains |publisher=CNN |accessdate=24 January 2012 |date=24 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 June, rebels recaptured the town of [[Kikla]] after Gaddafi forces pulled out of the town and retreated at around 9 kilometers of the city.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://af.reuters.com/article/libyaNews/idAFLDE75D17F20110614 | agency=Reuters | title=Rebels take control of Libyan town | date=14 June 2011}}</ref> Gaddafi troops also shelled the rebels around the border of Tunisia, with some rockets landing again on Tunisia soil.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://af.reuters.com/article/libyaNews/idAFLDE75D0P320110614 | agency=Reuters | title=UPDATE 2-Tunisia aircraft circle after Libya attack | date=14 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nBy 15 June, rebels had taken control of the previously contested town of Zawiet al-Baqool, located 20&nbsp;kilometers from Zintan. Pro-Gaddafi positions on the outskirts of the town were deserted, and retreating loyalist troops had left behind clothes, shoes and ammunition. Rebels also claimed that after the capture of the town, they were moving on to the loyalist held towns of Lawania and Ghanymma.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.africasia.com/services/news_mideast/article.php?ID=CNG.d8b17504535e4f19218999090de182f4.fd1 |title=Libya rebels make advances on road to Tripoli |publisher=Africasia.com |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> On the same day, rebels took over Lawania.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContent/2/0/14356/World/0/Libya-rebels-control-two-villages-in-west.aspx |title=Libya rebels control two villages in west |publisher=English.ahram.org.eg |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Meanwhile, Reuters correspondents in [[Gharyan]] reported that the city, occupied by loyalist forces since the beginning of March, was experiencing some unrest as rebels pushed closer to it.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/06/15/libya-idUSLDE75E29K20110615 |title=WRAPUP 1-Libyan rebels take new villages in Western Mountains |agency=Reuters |accessdate=24 January 2012 |first=Nick |last=Carey |date=15 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 June, rebels attacked the loyalist-held towns of Takut and Ghazaya, located north of Nalut. These towns had served as the base of operations from which loyalist troops had been attacking the Wazzin border crossing and Nalut. NATO had also struck loyalist positions in [['Ayn al Ghazaya]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/libyaNews/idAFLDE75F25S20110617?sp=true |title=Heavy fighting as Libyan rebels try to push out |agency=Reuters |date=17 June 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 June, heavy battles took place north of Nalut in the village of Takut, which was attacked by rebels day before. Eight rebels were reportedly killed and 13 wounded in the fighting while rebels claimed that they had killed 45 loyalists and destroyed six armoured vehicles.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/libyaNews/idAFLDE75H04B20110618 |title=Gun battles in Libya's Nalut kill 8-rebels |agency=Reuters |date=18 June 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nBy 20 June, rebels stopped their offensive against Ghazaya, after not being able to dislodge Gaddafi forces in the town during three days of fighting in which 15 opposition fighters were killed<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.deseretnews.com/mobile/article//700145402/Libya-says-NATO-airstrike-kills-9-civilians.html |title=Libya says NATO airstrike kills 9 civilians |work=Deseret News |date=19 June 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012 }}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/world/la-fg-libya-west-20110625,0,3393016.story?track=rss |title=Libyan's western front joins the battle |work=Los Angeles Times  |date=25 June 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012 |first=Borzou |last=Daragahi}}</ref> and 48 wounded.<ref>{{cite news|last=Law |first=Bill |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-14186310 |title=The road to recovery inside Libya's mountain hospital |publisher=BBC |date=20 July 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Also, rebels claimed to had shut off a pipeline in Rayayna that supplies the oil refinery in the loyalist-held city of [[Zawiya, Libya|Zawiya]] with crude oil from the [[Ubari]] oilfield. The report was later confirmed by ''[[The New York Times]]'' journalists.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/25/world/africa/25libya.html Rebels Arm Tripoli Guerrillas and Cut Resources to Capital]</ref> The following day, [[Human Rights Watch]] confirmed that loyalists had planted over 150 [[anti-personnel landmine]]s in at least one location in the mountains near the Tunisian border.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.aljazeera.net/liveblog/libya-jun-21-2011-1751 |title=Tuesday, June 21, 2011 \u2013 17:51 \u2013 Libya |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=21 June 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 June, loyalist forces tried to attack rebel fighters in Bir Ayyad from behind, thus cutting them off. In response rebel fighters launched a counter-attack on [[Bir al-Ghanam]], located 50&nbsp;kilometers south of [[Zawiya, Libya|Zawiya]]. At least two rebel fighters were killed during the fighting.<ref>{{cite web|author=ADAM SCHRECK Associated Press |url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory?id=13932793 |title=Libyan Rebels Make Advances in Western Mountains \u2013 AP |publisher=ABC News |date=26 June 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.aljazeera.net/liveblog/libya-jun-26-2011-1530 |title=Sunday, June 26, 2011 \u2013 14:30 \u2013 Libya |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=26 June 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-13921665 |title=Libya: Fierce fighting near to Tripoli |publisher=BBC |date=27 June 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 June, rebels managed to capture Al Qaa military barracks and ammunition depot, some 20 kilometers south of Zintan. Rebel fighters attacked the base at 6:00&nbsp;am with one group assigned to attack the base and a second to cut off reinforcements. At noon about 100 loyalist soldiers retreated to the nearby Twama base. Rebels lost two fighters in the battle and eight remained wounded.<ref>{{cite news|last=Weaver |first=Matthew |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/middle-east-live/2011/jun/28/libya-syria-middle-east-unrest-live |title=The Guardian Live Blog |work=The Guardian |location=UK |date=28 June 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/world/la-fg-libya-weapons-20110629,0,2814730.story |title=Libyan rebels seize massive weapons depot |work=Los Angeles Times  |date=29 June 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012 |first=Borzou |last=Daragahi}}</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/29/world/africa/29libya.html Libyan Base Falls to a Rebel Ambush in the West]</ref> The capture was confirmed by an [[Al Jazeera]] report (with video) which also noted that the weapons included two Russian tanks and that these ammunition gains would provide an \"enormous morale booster\" and greatly increase \"momentum...that the rebel forces have been building up for quite a while\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.aljazeera.net/liveblog/libya-jun-28-2011-1804 |title=Al Jazeera Libya Live Blog: Tuesday, June 28, 2011 \u2013 18:04 |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=28 June 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Later, a Reuters reporter stated that the rebels were actually not able to get all of the weapons because they were prevented after a fire that broke out across the whole depot.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/sns-rt-international-us-litre7270jp-20110426,0,7463062.story |title=\"Game over\" for Gaddafi in months: prosecutor |work=Chicago Tribune |accessdate=24 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609085448/http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/sns-rt-international-us-litre7270jp-20110426,0,7463062.story |archive-date=9 June 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe next day, 29 June, it was confirmed that, despite reports of a significant capture in arms by the rebels, they mostly captured ammunition and rockets, but no weapons to fire them from. Rebels had captured only two [[T-55]] tanks, dozens of military vehicles, dynamite, [[Strela 2|9M32M]] missiles (but without the missile launchers), boxes of ammunition (without guns for the ammunition), and dust-covered bombs. Most of the ammunition and bombs dated back decades, some to even 1972.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/world/la-fg-libya-weapons-20110629,0,2814730.story |title=Libya rebels seize Kadafi arms depot |work=Los Angeles Times  |date=29 June 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012 |first=Borzou |last=Daragahi}}</ref> Also, it was revealed that one of the two rebels killed did not die in battle but when he was attempting to forcefully open one of the boxes, like many others, who ripped apart ammunition cases with crowbars or gun butts. In addition, most of the 70 storage bunkers at the base were already previously partly or totally destroyed by NATO's airstrikes. Only a handful were still intact. By day's end the rebel momentum seemed to had faltered as hundreds of people fled the base, after a rumor that the pro-Gaddafi soldiers were returning, which they did not. A rebel from Jadu stated that, in contrast to previous rebel claims of a momentum gathering for a push on the capital, talk of an attack on Tripoli was premature. In his words \"We are going to have to organize ourselves out here first.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/29/world/africa/29libya.html?_r=1 |title=Libyan Base Falls to a Rebel Raid in the West |work=The New York Times |date=29 June 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012 |first=Kareem |last=Fahim}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 July, the rebel attack on [[Bir al-Ghanam]] faltered. Rebels were massing earlier in the day on a ridge near the town for an attack on the city. However, later, a heavy loyalist rocket barrage from inside Bir al-Ghanam hit the rebels forcing them to retreat from their positions on the outskirts of the town. Some of the rockets were landing as far back as Bir-Ayyad, 30 kilometers to the south. In the afternoon, a Reuters reporter claimed that the rebels had returned to the same positions on the outskirts of Bir al-Ghanam.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ca.reuters.com/article/topNews/idCATRE7270JP20110701 |title=Rockets push back rebels south of Libyan capital |agency=Reuters |date=1 July 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> However, the next day, a rebel military spokesman confirmed that the opposition forces had still not re-captured their previous positions and were hoping to accomplish that within the next 48 hours.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/libyaNews/idAFLDE76107S20110702 |title=Libya rebels say bracing for a new Tripoli push |agency=Reuters |date=2 July 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nDuring fighting between 30 June and 3 July, the rebels attempted to advance from [[Kikla]] toward the town of [[al-Qawalish]] (which holds a western and an eastern part, separated by a canyon). If they took the town the road would be open to [[Gharyan]]. However, the rebels were unable to move forward and nine opposition fighters were killed and dozens wounded.<ref name=\"Libya: Why is it taking so long\"/> During the battle, loyalist snipers took positions on a water tower between al-Qawalish and rebel positions, just few hundred meters away, at Kikla.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-14023595 |title=Libyan rebels outline their plans to attack Tripoli |publisher=BBC |date=4 July 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 July, rebels launched an attack on al-Qawalish with hundreds of fighters. They did so after NATO aircraft intensified bombing of the area and finally gave rebels the green light to advance.<ref>[http://thedailynewsegypt.com/region/libya-rebels-launch-assault-on-tripoli-gateway.html Libya rebels launch assault on Tripoli gateway]</ref> After several hours rebel fighters advanced a couple of kilometers towards al-Qawalish.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/libyaNews/idAFLDE7650HM20110706?sp=true |title=Western mountain rebels launch offensive southwest of Tripoli |agency=Reuters |date=6 July 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Al-Qawalish was finally captured after six hours of fighting.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/energyOilNews/idAFLDE7650YA20110706 |title=Libya rebels seize village from pro-Gaddafi forces |agency=Reuters |date=6 July 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> One rebel fighter was reportedly killed and five wounded during the opposition offensive. It was unclear if any government soldiers were killed.<ref>{{cite news|agency=Associated Press |url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2011/07/06/libyan-rebels-seize-two-mountain-towns-from-qaddafi-forces/ |title=Libyan Rebels Seize Two Mountain Towns From Qaddafi Forces |publisher=Fox News Channel |date=7 April 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> After the fall of al-Qawalish, the town was looted and burned by rebel forces over a period of two days, due to animosity between the Berber and the smaller [[Mashaashia]] tribe which takes residence in the village.<ref>{{cite news|author=C.J. Chivers |url=http://atwar.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/07/10/reporters-notebook-reading-the-rebels-in-western-libya-pt-i/?hp |title=Reporter's Notebook: Reading the Rebels in Western Libya, Part 1 |publisher=Atwar.blogs.nytimes.com |date=10 July 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Reports also emerged of burning, looting and even abuse of civilians in at least three other towns and villages that had been recently captured by the rebels.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-14135530 |title=Libyan rebels abused civilians: Human Rights Watch |publisher=BBC |date=13 July 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> In addition, the bodies of five loyalist soldiers were found rotting in a heap on the road between Qawalish and Um al-Jersan. They appeared to had been killed execution style, with three of them having their arms or legs bound.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/07/13/world/africa/13libya.html?_r=1 |title=Libyan Rebels Accused of Pillage and Beatings |work=The New York Times |date=13 July 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012 |first=C. J. |last=Chivers}}</ref>\n\n=== Rebel advance stopped ===\n;7\u201327 July\n\nOn 10 July, rebel-held al-Qawalish came under rocket attack by loyalist forces from Asabah, but the rebels did not retreat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/region/libya/gaddafi-forces-counterattack-southwest-of-tripoli-1.836255 |title=Gaddafi forces counterattack southwest of Tripoli |work=Gulf News |date=10 July 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 July, loyalist forces attacked Qawalish again. This time the rebels retreated, some of them claiming that they had to pull back because they ran out of ammunition. Government troops started the attack after a group of rebels attempted to advance east of the town toward Gharyan. The loyalists quickly swept through Qawalish from the east and reached as far as the checkpoint on the western edge of the village.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ca.reuters.com/article/topNews/idCATRE7270JP20110713?pageNumber=1&virtualBrandChannel=0 |title=Gaddafi troops retake village south of Tripoli |agency=Reuters |date=13 July 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> However, by the evening, the rebels counter-attacked. After a five-hour battle, they retook the town and chased loyalist forces to the outskirts of Asabah. During the fighting, eight rebels were killed and 27 wounded.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/07/14/world/africa/14libya.html?_r=1&ref=world | work=The New York Times | first=C. J. | last=Chivers | title=Rebel Forces Briefly Lose Control of Qawalish | date=13 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/07/13/libya.war/index.html?section=cnn_latest |title=Libyan rebels looted and beat civilians, rights group says |publisher=CNN |date=13 July 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/07/13/libya.war/index.html?section=cnn_latest |title=Libyan rebels say they have retaken village of Qawalish |publisher=CNN |date=13 July 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.ninemsn.com.au/world/8272643/libya-rebels-on-the-march |title=Libya rebels on the march |publisher=News.ninemsn.com.au |accessdate=24 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110912162547/http://news.ninemsn.com.au/world/8272643/libya-rebels-on-the-march |archivedate=12 September 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.realclearworld.com/news/reuters/international/2011/Jul/13/libya_rebels_retake_village_south_of_tripoli.html |title=Libya rebels retake village south of Tripoli |publisher=Realclearworld.com |date=13 July 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325225655/http://www.realclearworld.com/news/reuters/international/2011/Jul/13/libya_rebels_retake_village_south_of_tripoli.html |archive-date=25 March 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn 14 July, rebels retreated back to al-Qawalish from the outskirts of Asabah after reaching within 6&nbsp;km of the hamlet in order to regroup.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.aljazeera.net/liveblog/libya-jul-14-2011-1658 |title=Thursday, July 14, 2011 \u2013 15:58 \u2013 Libya |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=14 July 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The same day, rebels stated that they had run into and cleared a minefield made by loyalist forces near al-Qawalish.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.aljazeera.net/liveblog/libya-jul-14-2011-2125 |title=Thursday, July 14, 2011 \u2013 20:25 \u2013 Libya |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=14 July 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 July, Libyan opposition forces repelled an offensive by government troops against Qawalish. Witnesses said dozens of civilians were sent to the area just before the attack by the loyalists.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zimbio.com/Libya/articles/6YKo05HIeq8/Kadhafi+counter+attack+repulsed+Tripoli+bombed |title=Kadhafi counter-attack repulsed, Tripoli bombed |publisher=Zimbio.com |date=24 July 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The opposition forces claimed that the civilians were being used as human shields by government troops. However, the Libyan government stated that they were all Gaddafi supporters and state TV showed a convoy of civilians waving green flags which they stated was attacked by the rebels. One rebel was killed during the fighting, the 16-year-old son of the top rebel Zintan commander.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/07/24/libya.germany/ |title=Germany lends Libyan rebels $144 million as fighting rages |publisher=CNN |accessdate=24 January 2012 |date=24 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nAs the offensive in the eastern part of the mountains halted, rebels in the western part of the mountains planned a new offensive. On 27 July, correspondents reported seeing around 20 pickup tucks moving towards Nalut, while 30 more were congregating to the east. Omar Fakkan, a rebel commander, reported that rebels from Nalut and nearby towns were massing for a new offensive against [['Ayn al Ghazaya]] to be begun in the upcoming days.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.aljazeera.net/liveblog/libya-jul-27-2011-2155 |title=Wednesday, July 27, 2011 \u2013 21:55 \u2013 Libya |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=27 July 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Late July rebel offensive ===\n;28\u201331 July\n\nOn 28 July, rebels confirmed their earlier plans and attacked [['Ayn al Ghazaya]] and four other villages on the road between rebel-held Shakshuk and Ghazaya with infantry, technicals, tanks and rocket artillery. Hundreds of rebel fighters took part in the operation against an estimated 2,000 to 4,000 loyalist soldiers stationed in the valley.<ref>Abdallah, Diana (editor) (28 July 2011) [https://af.reuters.com/article/libyaNews/idAFL6E7IS0BL20110728 \"Libya rebels launch offensive on strategic town of Ghezaia\"] Reuters</ref> After several hours of fighting, rebel forces announced they had captured the towns of Takut, al-Ruwais, Badr and al-Jawsh, although loyalist forces retook al-Jawsh in a counterattack shortly afterwards. Further west, Ghazaya was bombarded by rebel artillery and tanks in an attempt to soften up defences before making an assault on the town.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/><ref>{{cite news|author=From Kareem Khadder and Michael Holmes, CNN |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/07/28/libya.war/ |title=Libyan rebels claim successes in offensive near Tunisia |publisher=CNN |accessdate=24 January 2012 |date=24 August 2011}}</ref> Eight hours since the start of the offensive, after heavy fighting and a bombardment by rebel artillery, the opposition claimed that loyalist troops pulled out of the town of Ghazaya.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-14321751 |title=Libya rebels 'capture key supply route town of Ghazaya' |publisher=BBC |date=28 July 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> But that claim was not confirmed by eather Al Jazeera or any other sources.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/africa/2011/07/2011728144624965299.html |title=Libya opposition arrests senior leader |publisher=English.aljazeera.net |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Also, later in the evening, [[The Guardian]] newspaper stated that fighting was still ongoing in the outskirts of the town.<ref>{{cite news|author=Chris Stephen in Misrata, and Lizzy Davies |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/jul/28/libyan-rebels-launch-major-offensive |title=Libyan rebels launch major offensive to capture key towns |work=The Guardian |location=UK |accessdate=24 January 2012 |date=28 July 2011}}</ref> The rebels also reported they captured the towns of al-Ruwais and Badr, and surrounded Umm al-Far. According to the opposition, they were negotiating with loyalist troops inside Umm al-Far.<ref>{{cite news|author=From Kareem Khadder and Michael Holmes, CNN |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/07/28/libya.war/index.html |title=Libyan rebel chief found dead in Benghazi |publisher=CNN |accessdate=24 January 2012 |date=24 August 2011}}</ref> Four rebels were killed during the offensive and 20 wounded.<ref>{{cite news|author=From Kareem Khadder and Michael Holmes, CNN |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/07/28/libya.war/index.html?section=cnn_latest |title=Libyan rebels claim successes in offensive near Tunisia |publisher=CNN |accessdate=24 January 2012 |date=24 August 2011}}</ref> The number of casualties among loyalist forces was unknown but 18 government soldiers were captured by the opposition troops.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/africaandindianocean/libya/8668502/Libya-rebels-launch-offensive-in-west.html Libya rebels launch offensive in west]</ref> The Gaddafi government claimed that 190 rebels were killed by 29 July, since the start of the offensive.<ref>{{cite news|author=Chris Stephen in Misrata, Lizzy Davies and Ian Traynor |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/jul/29/abdel-fatah-younis-death-libya |title=Abdel Fatah Younis assassination creates division among Libya rebels |work=The Guardian |location=UK |accessdate=24 January 2012 |date=29 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 July, the rebel offensive in the valley continued with opposition forces attacking the last loyalist stronghold in Tiji and surrounding the area. They were up against an estimated 500 loyalist soldiers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.aljazeera.net/liveblog/libya-jul-30-2011-2003 |title=Al Jazeera Live Blog |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=30 July 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Up to this point, the rebels had succeeded in capturing the villages of Hawamid, Takut, and Ghazaya in their drive to clear pro-Gaddafi forces from the mountain region's surroundings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/africa/2011/07/20117301751273757.html |title=Libyan rebels confirm Younes arrest warrant |publisher=English.aljazeera.net |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.aljazeera.net/liveblog/libya-jul-30-2011-1800 |title=Saturday, July 30, 2011 \u2013 18:00 \u2013 Libya |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=30 July 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 July, rebels recaptured the previously gained and lost village of al-Jawsh and were engaged in a battle for the town of Tiji in a strong sandstorm.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.aljazeera.net/liveblog/libya-jul-31-2011-1348 |title=Al Jazeera Live Blog |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=31 July 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> However, they lost al-Jawsh once again a day later when loyalists counterattacked, sending the rebels retreating half way along the road to the town of Shakshuk.<ref>{{cite web|author=Your name |url=http://www.emirates247.com/news/world/libya-rebels-round-up-kadhafi-militia-lose-village-2011-08-01-1.410807 |title=Libya rebels round up Kadhafi militia, lose village |publisher=Emirates247.com |date=1 August 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Reports showed that rebels were not acclaimed as liberators in Ghazaya, as all the 5,000 inhabitants escaped to pro-Gaddafi zones to avoid them. Rebels acknowledged that Tiji was also a pro-Gaddafi town.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/libyaNews/idAFLDE76U09620110731?pageNumber=1&virtualBrandChannel=0 |title=Western Mountain battle shows complexities of Libya conflict |agency=Reuters |date=31 July 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Rebel capture of Bir al-Ghanam ===\n;1\u201312 August\n\nOn 2 August, rebels had to stop their offensive on Tiji because they ran out of ammunition.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://af.reuters.com/article/libyaNews/idAFLDE77112X20110802?pageNumber=1&virtualBrandChannel=0 | agency=Reuters | title=REFILE-Libya rebels up for fight but where are the bullets? | date=2 August 2011}}</ref> The next day, three rebels were killed near Tiji by a Grad missile.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/commoditiesNews/idAFLDE7720ZF20110803 |title=Libya's western rebels losing patience with leaders |agency=Reuters |date=3 August 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 August, three rebels were killed near [[Bir al-Ghanam]]. Rebels also admitted that their offensive toward Tripoli had completely stalled after one month.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://af.reuters.com/article/libyaNews/idAFLDE77413V20110805?pageNumber=3&virtualBrandChannel=0 | agency=Reuters | title=In western Libya hopes for quick Tripoli advance fade | date=5 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 August, rebel officials said that they had set an ultimatum for Gaddafi forces to surrender in Tiji (which rebels claim is surrounded) by the following day. The rebels used loud-hailers to appeal to a tribal chief close to Colonel Gaddafi, to evacuate civilians from Tiji and broker the withdrawal or surrender of loyalist forces.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2011-08-05/government-denies-gaddafi27s-son-killed/2826928 |title=Reports of Gaddafi's son's death 'dirty lies' \u2013 ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation) |publisher=ABC |location=Australia  |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 August, rebels launched another attack on Bir al-Ghanam with hundreds of fighters, hoping to take the small town and thus opening their way towards Zawiya and other coastal cities.<ref>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/middle-east/Rebels-launch-push-in-western-Libya-aim-for-coast/articleshow/9511666.cms Rebels Launch Push In Western Libya, Aim For Coast]</ref> A few hours later, Bir al-Ghanam was under rebel control. Eight rebel fighters were killed during the attack while the number of killed loyalist forces remained unknown.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/08/06/libya.war/index.html |title=Rebels in western Libyan town claim victory over Gadhafi forces |publisher=CNN |date=6 August 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yuhOP8v2kc4 |title=Al Jazeera report from Bir al-Ghanam |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> According to the AFP, rebels were able to advance within 20&nbsp;km of the city of [[Sorman]] before encountering heavy resistance from loyalist forces and traded tank fire with them on the road to the coast.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.smh.com.au/breaking-news-world/libya-rebels-capture-town-near-tripoli-20110807-1ih46.html |title=Libya rebels capture town near Tripoli |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=7 August 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 August, the Libyan government announced that its forces had recaptured Bir al-Ghanam from anti-Gaddafi forces.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nation.co.ke/News/africa/Tripoli+says+key+town+recaptured+from+rebels/-/1066/1214932/-/hnk69kz/-/ |title=Tripoli says key town recaptured from rebels \u2013 Africa |work=Daily Nation |date=16 July 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> This was denied by the rebels who claimed that, on the contrary, they were able to push 10 more kilometers northeast from Bir al-Ghanam and were preparing to push towards [[Zawiya, Libya|Zawiya]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.cri.cn/6966/2011/08/08/2741s652325.htm |title=Libya Rebels Make Advances in West Front |publisher=English.cri.cn |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/commoditiesNews/idAFLDE77606U20110807?sp=true |title=WRAPUP 1-Libya rebels say they hold gains south of capital |agency=Reuters |date=7 August 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Rebel claims were later confirmed by an [[Al Jazeera]] and [[Reuters]] correspondent in the Nafusa mountains who also confirmed that rebels managed to push 30 kilometers towards city of Sorman and were positioned 50 kilometers outside of it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.aljazeera.net/liveblog/libya-aug-7-2011-2213 |title=Al Jazeera Libe Blog |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=7 August 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/commoditiesNews/idAFLDE7770FA20110808 |title=Rebels control town near Tripoli \u2013 Reuters reporter |agency=Reuters |date=8 August 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 August, five rebels were killed and 10 wounded in fighting near Bir al-Ghanam.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/world/2011-08-10-libya-nato-airstrikes_n.htm |title=NATO: Libya airstrike killed troops, not civilians |work=USA Today |accessdate=24 January 2012 |date=10 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/libyaNews/idAFLDE77913P20110810?pageNumber=2&virtualBrandChannel=0 |title=Rats, dogs and sundry insults fly at Libyan front |agency=Reuters |date=10 August 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Rebel commanders claimed to be 5 kilometers from Sorman's outskirts, and 20 from Zawiya's outskirts and were also making advances on the road towards the town of [['Aziziya]] directly south of Tripoli.<ref>[https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5gKEjKx0bB22IW81-NywiqKIlOVJg?docId=8dfaab06752a4b7fac39b9da92a64d1b ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110811114315/https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5gKEjKx0bB22IW81-NywiqKIlOVJg?docId=8dfaab06752a4b7fac39b9da92a64d1b |date=11 August 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOn 11 August, rebels captured the village of Shalghouda and claimed the capture of the villages of al-Nasr and Bir Shuaib, some 25 kilometers from Zawiya. One rebel fighter was killed and four wounded.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/libyaNews/idAFLDE77A0UN20110811?sp=true |title=Western Libya rebels strike north towards coast |agency=Reuters |date=11 August 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Rebel recapture of Gharyan, end of campaign ===\n{{Main|Battle of Gharyan}}\n;13\u201318 August\nOn 13 August, opposition forces managed to enter the strategic town of [[Gharyan]] and capture the city center after a four-hour battle which resulted in loyalist troops retreating. However, after a brief lull, government forces returned into Gharyan with a large number of reinforcements, and fighting in the city resumed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/africa/2011/08/2011813913965166.html |title=Gaddafi defiant as rebels claim gains in west \u2013 Africa |publisher=Al Jazeera |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 August, rebels stated that they controlled \"70 percent\" of the city.<ref>Al Jazeera Libya Live Blog. [http://blogs.aljazeera.net/liveblog/libya-aug-14-2011-1838 Sunday, 14 August 2011 \u2013 18:38 Entry]</ref>\n\nOn 15 August, rebels reported they controlled [[Gharyan]], although some reports suggested that fighting was still ongoing.<ref name=\"beeb\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-14523802|publisher=BBC News|title=Libya conflict: Rebels fight for key towns near Tripoli|date=15 August 2011|accessdate=15 August 2011}}</ref> The opposition forces also launched an attack against Tiji, where the Gaddafi government claimed 40 rebels were killed,<ref name=\"jkaradsheh\">{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/08/15/libya.war/|publisher=CNN|date=15 August 2011|accessdate=15 August 2011|title=High-level Tripoli government official leaves Libya|first=Jomana|last=Karadsheh}}</ref> though the rebels claimed they had taken the town.<ref name=\"beeb\"/> Later that day, Al Jazeera Arabic confirmed the fall of Tiji and stated that the rebels were moving against nearby Badr. Opposition forces also reportedly surrounded Assaba and were negotiating the surrender of loyalist soldiers trapped inside the village, though this claim could not be confirmed.<ref name=\"jkaradsheh\"/>\n\nOn 17 August, rebels claim to be in control of Badr.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/aug/17/gaddafi-troops-fight-city-zawiyah |location=London |work=The Guardian  | first1=Luke | last1=Harding | first2=Peter | last2=Beaumont | first3=Chris | last3=Stephen | title=Gaddafi troops fight to maintain positions in strategic city of Zawiyah | date=17 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 August, journalists confirmed that the rebels were in complete control of [[Gharyan]],<ref>Laessing, Ulf; Bell, Yvonne (18 August 2011). [https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/08/18/us-libya-idUSTRE77A2Y920110818 \"Libyan Rebels Seize Refinery, Eye Tripoli\"].  [[Reuters]]. Retrieved 18 August 2011.</ref> thus effectively driving the last loyalist forces from the Nafusa Mountains and marking the end of the Nafusa Mountains campaign.\n\n== Aftermath ==\n\n=== Rebel advance towards the coast, new front opens ===\n{{main|2011 Libyan rebel coastal offensive}}\nOn 13 August, [[Reuters]] confirmed that the rebels moved north from Al Nasr and advanced 7 kilometers towards Zawiya.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/topNews/idAFJOE77C03S20110813 |title=Libyan rebels advance on Zawiyah, battle in Brega |agency=Reuters |date=13 August 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref><ref>[http://www.dailyherald.com/article/20110813/news/708139874/ Heavy clashes as Libyan rebels enter Zawiya]</ref>\n\nOn 14 August, rebels captured the city of [[Sorman]] and that they lost 10 dead and 34 wounded fighting there.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/08/14/us-libya-rebels-surman-idUSTRE77D23P20110814 | agency=Reuters | title=Rebels say capture Surman just west of Tripoli | date=14 August 2011}}</ref> There was also ongoing in fighting city of [[Sabratha]], and the border crossing of [[Ras Ajdir]] had also been attacked.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/08/14/us-libya-idUSTRE77A2Y920110814 | agency=Reuters | title=Libyan rebels fly flag over key town near Tripoli | date=14 August 2011}}</ref> Later on the same day, a rebel spokesman announced the capture of [[Ajaylat]], though this could not be confirmed<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.aljazeera.net/liveblog/libya-aug-14-2011-2236 |title=Libya \u2013 Aug 14, 2011 \u2013 22:36 &#124; Al Jazeera Blogs |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=14 August 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> A later [[Ann Marlowe|journalist]] report confirmed that [[Sorman]] had fallen earlier, and stated that [[Sabratha]] had been taken on 15 August after loyalist forces fled in the afternoon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weeklystandard.com/blogs/fight-sabratha_590281.html?page=3 |title=The Fight for Sabratha |work=The Weekly Standard |date=16 August 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Consequences ===\nThe conflict has had humanitarian impacts. [[M\u00e9decins Sans Fronti\u00e8res]] sent a team to help with wounded in [[Zintan]].<ref name=\"msf.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.msf.org/msf/articles/2011/05/msf-expands-operations-in-response-to-growing-needs-in-libya.cfm |title=MSF expands operations in response to growing needs in Libya |publisher=M\u00e9decins Sans Fronti\u00e8res |accessdate=24 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120323005325/http://www.msf.org/msf/articles/2011/05/msf-expands-operations-in-response-to-growing-needs-in-libya.cfm |archivedate=23 March 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> As of 21 May, Al Galaa was reported to be without water and electricity for seven weeks.<ref name=\"msf.org\"/> Also, more than 45,000 Libyan refugees were reported in the Tunisian region of [[Tataouine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tap.info.tn/en/en/regions/2575-more-than-45000-libyan-refugees-in-tataouine.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110525014523/http://www.tap.info.tn/en/en/regions/2575-more-than-45000-libyan-refugees-in-tataouine.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=25 May 2011 |title=More than 45,000 Libyan refugees in Tataouine |publisher=Tap.info.tn |accessdate=24 January 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2011, [[Le Figaro]] reported that France secretly [[airdrop]]ped significant quantities of arms in the Nafusa Mountains for the Berber rebels.<ref>{{in lang|fr}} [http://www.lefigaro.fr/international/2011/06/28/01003-20110628ARTFIG00704-la-france-a-parachute-des-armes-aux-rebelles-libyens.php La France a parachut\u00e9 des armes aux rebelles libyens], Philippe Gelie, 28 June 2011, ''Le Figaro''</ref> The arms included assault rifles, machine guns, rocket-propelled grenades, and European-made [[MILAN]] anti-tank missiles. The French government later confirmed the reports, stating that the airdrops had started in June.<ref>[https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5gst8wAKgJwnMvBWiTl9EQ1Zpylmg?docId=CNG.041943dc452c61a507ee986061b49f2d.1031 France gives Libya rebels arms but Britain balks], Agence France-Presse \u2013 29 June 2011</ref> On 5 July, French defense minister [[G\u00e9rard Longuet]] declared that the airdrops had ceased.<ref>{{in lang|fr}} [http://www.lefigaro.fr/flash-actu/2011/07/05/97001-20110705FILWWW00306-libye-plus-de-parachutages-d-armes.php Libye: plus de parachutages d'armes], Agence France-Presse 5 July 2011</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Libyan civil war}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nafusa Mountains campaign}}\n[[Category:Battles of the Libyan Civil War (2011)]]\n[[Category:Military history of Libya]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{lead too short|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict= 2011 Nafusa Mountains campaign\n|partof= the [[2011 Libyan Civil War|Libyan Civil War]]\n|image= Gaddafi loyalist in the Nafusa Mountains.png\n|caption= Gaddafi loyalist in the Nafusa Mountains\n|date= 1 March \u2013 18 August 2011\n|place= [[Nafusa Mountains]], Libya\n|territory=\n* Pro-Gaddafi forces retake [[Gharyan]], [[Kikla]], [[Yafran]] and [[Rayayna]] from early March to late May, but lose all of their gains except Gharyan in June.\n* Rebel-held al Galaa cut off and surrounded by pro-Gaddafi forces until the recapture of [[Yafran]]\n* Rebels capture and hold the [[Wazzin]] border crossing, with some clashes spilling into [[Tunisia]].\n* Rebels capture all towns around the mountains from June to August.\n* Rebels capture Gharyan on 18 August.\n|result= Anti-Gaddafi victory\n* Rebels start an [[2011 Libyan rebel coastal offensive|offensive toward the coast]] in mid-August.\n|combatant1= '''{{flagicon|Libya|1951}} [[Anti-Gaddafi forces]]'''\n* [[National Liberation Army (Libya)|National Liberation Army]]\n----\n'''{{flag|Tunisia}}'''<ref>{{cite news| url=https://af.reuters.com/article/libyaNews/idAFLDE73S0PB20110429 | work=Reuters | title=Tunisia troops clash with Gaddafi forces -resident | date=29 April 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Tunisian Army]]\n* Tunisian Police\n----\n'''{{flagicon|United Nations}} [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 1973|UNSC Resolution 1973 forces]]'''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2011/03/18/3167294.htm|title=UN clears way for Libyan no-fly zone|date=18 March 2011}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|NATO}} [[2011 military intervention in Libya|NATO command]]<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.dawn.com/2011/03/25/nato-to-enforce-no-fly-zone-over-libya.html| title=Nato takes control of enforcing Libya no-fly zone| accessdate=26 March 2011 | date=25 March 2011}}</ref>\n|combatant2= '''{{flagicon|Libya|1977}} [[Armed forces of the Libyan Arab Jamahiriya]]'''\n|commander1={{flagicon|Libya|1951}} Col. Mokhtar Milad Fernana<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/world/la-fg-libya-rebels-20110701,0,3175715.story |title=Rebels in Libya's west gain ground |work=Los Angeles Times  |date=1 July 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012 |first=Borzou |last=Daragahi}}</ref><br><small>(overall commander)</small><br>{{flagicon|Libya|1951}} Cdr. [[Mohammed Ali Madani]]{{KIA}}<ref>{{cite web|author=AFP Wednesday, 7 September 2011 |url=http://news.asiaone.com/News/AsiaOne%2BNews/World/Story/A1Story20110907-298177.html |title=Libya's Zintan Brigade refuses to leave Tripoli |publisher=News.asiaone.com |date=7 September 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref><br><small>(1st Zintan commander)</small><br>{{flagicon|Libya|1951}} Cdr. Hajj Usama<ref name=\"cnn.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/05/20/libya.war/index.html?eref=rss_mostpopular |title=Fierce fighting in Libya's western mountains |publisher=CNN |date=20 May 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref><br><small>(2nd Zintan commander)</small><br>{{flagicon|Libya|1951}} Cdr. Ali al-Hajj (Yafran commander)<ref name=\"Libya: Why is it taking so long\">{{cite news|last=Doyle |first=Mark |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-14016620 |title=Libya: Why is it taking so long? |publisher=BBC |date=4 July 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n|commander2={{flagicon|Libya|1977}} Col. Shu'ayb al-Firjani<br><small>(Zintan area)</small><ref>{{cite news|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/world/94412/libya-gaddafi-war-lieutenants|title=Why Ar